        process: [
          { title: "Urgent Deadline Assessment", desc: "We immediately assess the applicable appeal deadline — which can be as short as 30 days — and file any urgently required notices to preserve your appeal rights before they are extinguished." },
          { title: "Grounds of Appeal Analysis", desc: "We identify the strongest available grounds for appeal — legal error, procedural irregularity, disproportionate penalty, failure to follow due process, or failure to consider material evidence." },
          { title: "Internal Review & Formal Appeal Filing", desc: "We pursue the optimal challenge route — internal administrative review where required or beneficial, followed by formal appeal before the competent tribunal or the Board of Grievances." },
          { title: "Appeal Hearing & Remedy", desc: "We present your appeal with full legal submissions, represent you at the hearing, and pursue the maximum available remedy — annulment, reversal, variation, or compensation." },
        ],
        faqs: [
          { q: "What is the deadline for appealing an administrative decision in Saudi Arabia?", a: "Administrative appeal deadlines in Saudi Arabia vary by authority and type of decision, but are typically 30–60 days from the date the decision is notified to you. Some specialist regulatory bodies have their own timelines. Missing the deadline can permanently bar your appeal. Qanoni acts immediately upon receiving a mandate — assessing the applicable deadline and filing any urgently required notices on the same day where necessary." },
          { q: "What grounds can I use to appeal an administrative decision in Saudi Arabia?", a: "Grounds for challenging an administrative decision include: (1) legal error — the authority applied the wrong law or misinterpreted the applicable regulation; (2) procedural error — the decision-making process was irregular or your right to be heard was not observed; (3) disproportionality — the sanction or decision was disproportionate to the facts; (4) insufficient reasoning — the authority failed to adequately explain its decision; (5) failure to consider material evidence. Qanoni identifies the strongest available grounds for your specific situation." },
          { q: "Can I get online advice on challenging an administrative decision in Saudi Arabia?", a: "Yes — and given the urgency of appeal deadlines, we strongly recommend contacting us as soon as you receive an adverse administrative decision. Qanoni provides immediate online consultation via WhatsApp or email. Share the decision and the relevant background, and our specialist will advise on your appeal rights and immediate next steps within minutes." },
          { q: "Can I challenge an administrative decision while complying with it?", a: "In most cases, yes — filing an administrative appeal does not automatically suspend the effect of the decision. However, you can apply for interim relief (a stay) to suspend the decision's effect while the appeal is pending, provided you can demonstrate sufficient grounds. Qanoni advises on the best approach for your specific decision — including whether to comply, challenge, or seek a stay — based on the facts and applicable law." },
        ],
