        faqs: [
          { q: "Must contracts be in Arabic to be enforceable in Saudi Arabia?", a: "Arabic is the official language of Saudi courts, and any contract submitted in evidence must be in Arabic or accompanied by a certified Arabic translation. Relying on an English-only contract in Saudi litigation creates significant procedural risk — translation disputes can undermine the enforceability of your key provisions. Qanoni drafts fully bilingual Arabic-English contracts that are immediately usable in Saudi courts without translation risk." },
          { q: "What makes a contract legally valid in Saudi Arabia?", a: "Under Saudi law, a valid contract requires: a clear offer and acceptance; lawful subject matter (not contrary to Sharia or public policy); mutual consent free of duress, fraud, or misrepresentation; and consideration (counter-performance). Saudi law does not generally require contracts to be notarised to be valid — but notarisation and registration is required or strongly advisable for certain contract types (real estate, corporate). Qanoni advises on validity requirements for your specific contract type." },
          { q: "What penalty clauses are enforceable in Saudi Arabian contracts?", a: "Saudi law permits contractual penalty clauses (shart jazaiy / gharama) — agreed sums payable on breach — and Saudi courts will generally enforce them unless they are grossly disproportionate to the actual loss. Courts retain discretion to increase or reduce penalty clause amounts where they are unconscionably low or high. Qanoni structures penalty clauses to be both commercially effective and legally defensible before Saudi courts." },
          { q: "Can contracts be concluded and signed electronically in Saudi Arabia?", a: "Yes. Saudi Arabia's Electronic Transactions Law recognizes electronic signatures and electronically concluded contracts as legally valid for most purposes. However, certain contract types — including real estate transactions, wills, and certain government contracts — still require physical execution or notarisation. Qanoni advises on the appropriate execution method for your specific contract and counterparty relationship." },
        ],
